We must “build” the current‐liabilities figure from the transactions by “picking out” those entries that increased a “payable” balance – namely, purchase transactions that were entered as “Unpaid” and which use an “Account Payable” payment method. (All of the “Initial” entries simply create assets, and none of the expenses or sales data add to current liabilities.) 

In the data the following purchase entries are “Unpaid” (thus “owing money” and counted as current liabilities):

1. Purchase20231231002  
  Amount = 1,495,000.00  
  (Payment Method = Account Payable)

2. Purchase20231231008  
  Amount = 21,150.00  
  (Account Payable)

3. Purchase20231231010  
  Amount = 256,080.00  
  (Account Payable)

4. Purchase20231231015  
  Amount = 39,900.00  
  (Account Payable)

5. Purchase20231231016  
  Amount = 46,550.00  
  (Account Payable)

6. Purchase20231231017  
  Amount = 97,650.00  
  (Account Payable)

7. Purchase20231231020  
  Amount = 524,160.00  
  (Account Payable)

8. Purchase20231231021  
  Amount = 15,150.00  
  (Account Payable)

9. Purchase20231231022  
  Amount = 838,080.00  
  (Account Payable)

We now add these (note: money amounts are taken from the “amount” column):

 • 1,495,000.00  
+ 21,150.00  
= 1,516,150.00

+ 256,080.00  
= 1,772,230.00

+ 39,900.00  
= 1,812,130.00

+ 46,550.00  
= 1,858,680.00

+ 97,650.00  
= 1,956,330.00

+ 524,160.00  
= 2,480,490.00

+ 15,150.00  
= 2,495,640.00

+ 838,080.00  
= 3,333,720.00

None of the “Initial” transactions (which date 2023‑12‑31) create any liabilities – they set up assets only. (For example, the bank and cash deposits and the fixed asset purchase are asset side entries.) Therefore, the “starting” (or “initial”) current liabilities answer is zero.

Thus, in our final balance‐sheet–figures the current liabilities initially are 0.00 and at the “end” (after all transactions) the current liabilities – based solely on the “unpaid” purchase amounts – equal 3,333,720.00.

  }
